Part I - Ford GoBike

by Tala Jebrini

Introduction

In this project, I will explore and visualize data from the Ford GoBike bike-sharing system, specifically the February 2019 trip data. The dataset contains information about individual bike trips taken in the San Francisco Bay Area, including trip duration, user type, station locations, and rider demographics.

The project is divided into two main parts:

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) I will use Python visualization libraries such as Pandas, Matplotlib, and Seaborn to analyze patterns and relationships in the data. This includes univariate, bivariate, and multivariate analysis to understand user behavior, trip duration patterns, and station popularity.

  2. Explanatory Data Visualization I will present the most interesting findings from the EDA using polished, well-designed visualizations. These visualizations will help communicate insights clearly and effectively to an audience.

The goal of this project is to demonstrate the power of data visualization in uncovering trends and sharing insights from real-world datasets.

Dataset Overview

The dataset used in this project is the Ford GoBike System Data for February 2019, available on Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/chirag02/ford-gobike-2019feb-tripdata

This dataset includes detailed information on 183,412 individual bike trips made in the San Francisco Bay Area during February 2019. Each record corresponds to one trip and includes the following key attributes:

  • duration_sec: Length of the trip in seconds.
  • start_time, end_time: Timestamps of when the trip started and ended.
  • start_station_id, end_station_id: Unique identifiers for the stations.
  • start_station_name, end_station_name: Names of the start and end stations.
  • start_lat, start_lon, end_lat, end_lon: Geographic coordinates of stations.
  • bike_id: Identifier of the bike used.
  • user_type: Indicates whether the rider was a Subscriber (monthly/yearly member) or Customer (casual rider).
  • member_gender and member_birth_year: Demographic information about the user.
  • bike_share_for_all_trip: Whether the trip was part of the Bike Share for All program.

This dataset is well-suited for time-based, location-based, and demographic analysis, offering great potential for discovering insights about urban mobility patterns.

Dataset Assessment Function

The assess_dataframe() function is a utility to quickly inspect the structure and quality of a dataset. It performs the following checks:

  • Missing Values: Shows how many null values exist in each column.
  • Duplicate Rows: Counts any duplicate entries.
  • Data Types: Displays the type of data in each column.
  • Info Summary: Gives an overview of the dataframes shape and memory usage.
  • Descriptive Statistics: Summarizes key statistics (mean, min, max, etc.) for numeric columns.

This function helps guide data cleaning decisions and ensures the dataset is ready for analysis.

In[4]:
def assess_dataframe(df, name):
    print(f"#  Dataset Assessment - {name}")
    print("\n Missing Values (.isnull().sum()):")
    print(df.isnull().sum())

    print("\n" + "="*80)
    print(" Duplicate Rows (.duplicated()):")
    print("Total Duplicates:", df.duplicated().sum())

    print("\n" + "="*80)
    print(" Data Types (.dtypes):")
    print(df.dtypes)

    print("\n" + "="*80)
    print(" DataFrame Info (.info()):")
    df.info()

    print("\n" + "="*80)
    print(" Descriptive Statistics (.describe()):")
    print(df.describe())

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset consists of 183,412 rows and 16 columns, where each row represents a bike trip taken in February 2019 in the San Francisco Bay Area. It includes both numerical features (e.g., duration_sec, member_birth_year, coordinates) and categorical features (e.g., user_type, member_gender, start_station_name).

  • No duplicate rows found.
  • Missing values exist in:
    • start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name 197 missing
    • member_birth_year, member_gender 8,265 missing
  • start_time and end_time are stored as strings (object) and should be converted to datetime format for time-based analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The primary feature of interest is duration_sec, which represents the trip duration in seconds. I aim to understand what factors influence the length of a trip and how it differs based on user type, gender, time of day, and other conditions.

What features support your investigation?

The following features will help support the analysis of trip duration:

  • start_time, end_time for extracting hour, day, and weekday/weekend trends.
  • user_type to compare trip behavior between Subscribers and Customers.
  • member_gender, member_birth_year for exploring demographic influences.
  • start_station_name, end_station_name to detect popular routes and location-based patterns.
  • bike_share_for_all_trip to evaluate differences in behavior for affordability program participants.

Data Cleaning

In[6]:
# Step 1: Convert time columns to datetime
bike['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike['start_time'])
bike['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike['end_time'])

# Step 2: Drop rows with missing demographic or station name data
bike_clean = bike.dropna(subset=['start_station_name', 'end_station_name', 'member_gender', 'member_birth_year'])

# Step 3: Filter out unrealistic trip durations (e.g., less than 1 minute or more than 2 hours)
bike_clean = bike_clean[(bike_clean['duration_sec'] >= 60) & (bike_clean['duration_sec'] <= 7200)]

# Step 4: Extract hour and day for later exploration
bike_clean['start_hour'] = bike_clean['start_time'].dt.hour
bike_clean['day_of_week'] = bike_clean['start_time'].dt.day_name()

Data Cleaning Steps

Before conducting univariate analysis, basic cleaning was applied:

  • Converted start_time and end_time to datetime format to allow time-based analysis.
  • Removed rows with missing values in key columns like station names, member_gender, and member_birth_year, since these fields are essential for demographic and location-based insights.
  • Filtered trip durations to keep only reasonable values (between 60 seconds and 2 hours).
  • Created new features:
    • start_hour: Hour of day the trip started
    • day_of_week: Name of the weekday the trip occurred

These steps ensure that the upcoming visualizations are based on clean and reliable data.

In[9]:
def setup_plot(title='', xlabel='', ylabel='', figsize=(10, 6), log_x=False, rotation=0):
    """
    Set up a consistent plot layout for any seaborn/matplotlib chart.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    if log_x:
        plt.xscale('log')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest

The distribution of duration_sec is clearly right-skewed, with the majority of trips lasting under 1,000 seconds (approximately 16 minutes). Very long trips are rare, but they extend the tail of the distribution significantly. This skew is typical in usage data, where most users take shorter trips. A log transformation or filtering could improve visibility of detail in the lower range.

Were there any unusual distributions or transformations?

No transformation was applied yet, but the long-tailed nature of duration_sec suggests it may be helpful in future steps.

In terms of categorical variables:

  • User Type shows a strong imbalance, with most trips taken by Subscribers rather than Customers.
  • Interestingly, the average trip duration is longer for Customers than Subscribers, which may indicate different use patterns (e.g., recreational vs. commuting).

No significant data quality issues were observed in the univariate distributions after initial cleaning.

Comparison: Scatter Plot vs. Line Plot for Trip Duration and Start Hour

1 Scatter Plot: Trip Duration vs. Start Hour The scatter plot displays individual trip durations across each hour of the day. While it technically shows the full dataset, the large volume of overlapping points makes it difficult to identify clear patterns or trends. The repeated vertical strips show that trips are evenly distributed across all hours, but the density and vertical spread make interpretation difficult.

2 Line Plot: Average Trip Duration by Start Hour In contrast, the line plot aggregates trip duration into hourly averages, making patterns much more apparent. It reveals:

  • A morning dip in average duration (likely commuters)
  • A midday peak between 11 AM and 3 PM (possibly leisure trips)
  • A gradual evening decline after 4 PM

I find the line plot is more effective for this analysis. While the scatter plot shows raw data, it suffers from overplotting. The line plot simplifies the data and makes trends much clearer, especially when comparing behavior across different times of day.

Box Plot: Trip Duration by User Type

This box plot illustrates the distribution of trip durations for Subscribers and Customers:

  • Customers tend to take longer trips overall, with a higher median trip duration and a wider interquartile range (IQR).
  • Subscribers have shorter, more consistent trip durations, likely reflecting frequent but brief commutes.
  • Both groups show a number of outliers, especially for longer trips, but the spread is noticeably greater among Customers.

This visualization reinforces the idea that Subscribers are likely daily users with routine usage, while Customers may be more occasional or recreational riders.

Clustered Bar Chart: User Type Distribution by Day of Week

This chart highlights how bike usage varies across weekdays and weekends for Subscribers and Customers:

  • Subscribers dominate usage on weekdays, particularly from Tuesday to Friday, likely due to commuting routines.
  • Their usage drops noticeably over the weekend, which supports the idea that their trips are primarily work-related.
  • Customers, on the other hand, maintain a more balanced pattern across the week, with slightly higher usage on weekends, suggesting more recreational or casual use.

This visualization effectively reinforces the behavioral distinction between the two user types: structured weekday usage by Subscribers vs. more flexible, leisure-oriented usage by Customers.

How did the main feature vary with other variables?

  • Trip Duration vs. Start Hour: Average trip durations are shorter during commuting hours (79 AM and 46 PM), likely reflecting quick, routine travel. Midday hours (10 AM3 PM) show longer average durations, suggesting leisure-oriented usage during off-peak times.

  • Trip Duration by User Type: Customers generally take longer trips than Subscribers. This indicates differing usage patterns with Subscribers likely using bikes for short, regular commutes, while Customers use them more occasionally and for longer rides.

Other notable relationships:

  • User Type by Day of Week: Subscriber usage peaks on weekdays, aligning with workweek routines. In contrast, Customer activity is more balanced but shows a relative increase on weekends, reflecting recreational or flexible usage.

Summary

These patterns support the hypothesis that trip duration and timing are significantly influenced by user type and day of the week, revealing two distinct rider behaviors: structured, commuter-driven Subscribers and more flexible, leisure-oriented Customers.

Faceted Scatter Plot: Trip Duration by Start Hour, Faceted by User Type and Day of Week

This multivariate FacetGrid plot provides a deep view into how trip duration varies by hour of day, across different user types and days of the week:

  • Customers (right column) show more scattered and longer trips, especially in the midday to afternoon hours. Their activity is more evenly distributed and notably visible on weekends, supporting the idea of recreational or casual usage.

The plot reinforces previous findings:

  • Subscribers use the system mainly on weekdays with shorter durations tied to commuting.
  • Customers are less predictable and tend to ride longer during off-peak hours, particularly on Saturday and Sunday.

This visualization strengthens the conclusion that time, user type, and day of week interact meaningfully to shape how and when people use the bike-sharing system.

Yes. In the faceted count plot of "Bike Share for All" participation, it was surprising to see that:

  • Male Subscribers are the most frequent participants in the program.
  • Customers, across all genders, showed very low participation, even though the program is designed for affordability and accessibility.

This suggests that the program may be more visible or appealing to long-term users (Subscribers) rather than occasional riders (Customers), and gender may also play a role in program awareness or accessibility.

These findings demonstrate how multivariate analysis can reveal hidden patterns and provide more context for interpreting user behavior.

Conclusions

This data exploration of the Ford GoBike system (February 2019) revealed valuable insights into how bike usage patterns vary by time, user type, gender, and participation in public access programs.

Summary of Key Findings:

  1. Trip Duration:

    • Most trips are short, with the majority under 1,000 seconds.
    • The distribution is heavily right-skewed with a long tail of longer rides.

  2. User Type Behavior:

    • Subscribers dominate the system, especially on weekdays.
    • Customers take fewer trips but tend to have longer durations.

  3. Time-Based Patterns:

    • Peak usage for Subscribers occurs during commuting hours (79 AM and 46 PM).
    • Customers ride more during midday hours and show increased usage on weekends, likely for recreational purposes.

  4. Demographic Influence:

    • Gender differences in trip duration are minor, but participation in the Bike Share for All program is notably higher among male Subscribers.

  5. Program Participation:

    • The Bike Share for All program sees minimal involvement from Customers, raising questions about its visibility or relevance for casual users.

  6. Multivariate Insights:

    • Faceted plots showed clear interactions between start_hour, day_of_week, and user_type, validating the commuter vs. recreational divide.
    • Participation patterns in the bike-share program vary not only by user type but also by gender, with female users participating less overall.

Reflection on the Exploration Process

  • The analysis began with basic wrangling and cleaning (handling null values and filtering unrealistic durations).
  • Univariate exploration helped understand the structure of key variables.
  • Bivariate analysis revealed patterns between time, user type, and duration.
  • Multivariate visualizations added depth, exposing behavioral patterns and demographic participation in public programs.

This project clearly demonstrates how thoughtful data visualization helps uncover user behavior trends, program reach, and urban mobility patterns, which can directly inform decisions in urban planning and accessibility policy.
